{meta: title Wabash Cannonball}
{meta: artist Hank Thompson}
{meta: writer W.M. Kindt}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]From the great Atlantic ocean 
To the wide Pacific [F]shore
From the queen of the flowing [G7]mountains 
To the south-bells by the [C]shore
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
She's mighty tall and handsome
And known quite well by [F]all
She's a regular [G7]combination 
On the Wabash [C]Cannonball
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
Listen to the jingle
To the rumble [F]and the roar
As she glides along the [G7]woodland 
Through the hills and by the [C]shore
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
Hear the mighty rush of the engine
Hear that lonesome hoboes [F]call
You're traveling through the [G7]jungle 
On the Wabash [C]Cannonball
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
She came down from Birmingham
One cold December [F]day
As she rolled into the [G7]station 
You could hear all the people [C]say
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
Now there's a gal from Tennessee
She's long and she's [F]tall
She came down from [G7]Birmingham 
On the Wabash [C]Cannonball
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 7}
Our eastern states are dandy
So the people always [F]say
From New York to St [G7]Louis 
And Chicago by the [C]way
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 8}
From the hills of Minnesota
Where the rippling waters [F]fall
No changes can [G7]be taken 
On the Wabash [C]Cannonball
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 9}
Here's to daddy Claxton
May his name forever [F]stand
And long to be [G7]remembered 
Round the ports of [C]Alabam
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 10}
His earthly race is over
And the curtains round him [F]fall
We'll carry [G7]him home to Dixie 
On the Wabash [C]Cannonball
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 11}
Listen to the jingle
The rumble and the [F]roar
As she glides along the [G7]woodland 
Through the hills and by the [C]shore
{end_of_verse}

